<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Agropyron cristatum </i>is a non-native, cool-season, medium-height bunchgrass that is long-lived, growing more than 30 years. Plants develop extensive fibrous roots, and they are tolerant of cold and drought conditions. It grows best on medium-textured soils, from sandy loams to clay loams (Asay and Knowles 1985, Ogle 2001, Zlatnik 1999b). <i>A. cristatum </i>reproduces primarily by seed or sometimes by rhizomes. Seedlings are very hardy, vigorous, and easily established. Seeds germinate earlier, and plants green up 2-4 weeks earlier than native bunchgrasses (Johnson 1986, Ogle 2001). <i>A. cristatum </i>is part of closely related group of interfertile taxa treated variously in different taxonomic treatments. The USDA-NRCS (2007) recognized three species: <i>A. cristatum, A. desertorum, </i>and <i>A. fragile</i>. Barkworth (2007) included <i>A. desertorum </i>in <i>A. cristatum, </i>and we use this name in the manual. <br/>
<br/>
<i>Agropyron cristatum </i>is an Old World introduction that grows in many alliances, especially on disturbed sites. Ranchers have planted thousands of hectares in the arid and semi-arid West to improve forage for use by livestock; it is palatable to wildlife, including antelope, deer, elk, birds, and small rodents. It naturalizes and dominates large areas, especially from northern parts of transmontane California east to the northwestern Great Plains (NatureServe 2007a, Ogle 2001). In conjunction with plantings, grazing pressures and changes in fire regime have caused shifts in native sagebrush stands with native understories of <i>Achnatherum hymenoides, Elymus elymoides, Festuca idahoensis, Leymus cinereus, </i>and <i>Poa secunda </i>into non-native understories or stands of <i>A. cristatum </i>and/or <i>Bromus tectorum. </i> </div>
</div>

    
	
	
